---

## Abstract

Our existing `/invoke` endpoint (V0/V1) returns a Leo-specific envelope (`GepReturnDto`) that drops widgets, has no ordering between text and widgets, leaks internal state, and doesn't validate inputs. It's fine for chat-UI fallbacks but unusable when an agent has to be called like an API — by another service, an automation, or a third-party integration.

Invoke V2 replaces it with `POST /v2/workflow-engine/:id/invoke`, which returns an **A2A Message** (Google's open Agent-to-Agent protocol): an ordered `parts[]` of text and widgets, plus a clean `metadata` block. It works by reusing the existing streaming pipeline and having a subscriber (`A2AStreamCollector`) assemble the AG-UI event stream into an A2A Message. No new state variables, no schema changes required on existing workflows.

---

## 1. Why this ADR exists

### The two ways agents are consumed today

| Transport | Endpoint | Who calls it |
|---|---|---|
| Streaming (SSE) | `POST /workflow-engine/:id/stream` | Chat UI, copilots, embedded assistants |
| Invoke (V0/V1) | `POST /workflow-engine/:id/invoke` | Legacy server-to-server callers |

The streaming path is feature-complete: it carries text tokens, tool calls, step events, widgets, HITL interrupts, and reasoning events — all as AG-UI events. The invoke path was bolted on later. It blocks on `compiledGraph.invoke()` and returns:

```json
{
  "isSuccess": true,
  "returnValue": {
    "messages": [...],
    "selectedAgentId": "...",
    "state": { "flow": {}, "system": {}, "nodes": {} }
  }
}

What's wrong with that
1) Widgets are lost. PV (Partial-View) widgets are dispatched as CUSTOM SSE events (PV_PRE_RENDER / PV_TEMPLATE / PV_POST_RENDER). The blocking invoke() path never sees them, so the response only contains text.
2) No content ordering. If the agent produces text → widget → text, there's nowhere in the response to represent that sequence.
3) Proprietary format. Every consumer has to learn GepReturnDto. No open standard.
4) State leaks. The full flow / system / nodes state is exposed alongside the answer, with no clean way to separate "the answer" from "internals".
5) No input validation. A badly shaped request starts executing anyway; the LLM sees garbage and either hallucinates or crashes mid-run.

Why now
Product direction is moving toward agents as APIs — callable by other services, automations, agent-to-agent orchestrators, and external integrations. None of those consumers want a chat UI; they want a structured, ordered, standards-compliant response. V1 doesn't deliver that.

