2. The decision
In one sentence
Invoke V2 runs the same streaming pipeline as /stream, and a subscriber called A2AStreamCollector turns the AG-UI event stream into an A2A Message.

That's it. No new state variables. No output-node templating. No per-node wiring. If a workflow streams correctly, it invokes correctly.

sequenceDiagram
    participant Client
    participant Controller as invokeV2()
    participant Service as execute()
    participant Adapter as streamExecutionObservable()
    participant Collector as A2AStreamCollector

    Client->>Controller: POST /v2/.../invoke
    Controller->>Service: execute(id, dto)
    Service->>Adapter: stream (streamMode: 'verbose')
    Adapter-->>Collector: AG-UI events (text, widgets, HITL, ...)
    Note over Collector: accumulates parts[] in order
    Adapter-->>Collector: RUN_FINISHED (output)
    Collector-->>Service: A2AMessage
    Service-->>Controller: A2AMessage
    Controller-->>Client: 200 OK (A2A JSON)

Why not the alternatives
Two other approaches were considered (and one was even implemented before being removed):

Option	What it is	Why we didn't ship it
A. Stream-and-collect ✅
This ADR. Reuse stream events; collector builds parts
Chosen
B. Template parsing
User writes finalAnswer on the output node with {{variable}} placeholders; transformer parses it into parts
Every workflow needs a correctly-authored template; missing {{system.artifacts}} silently drops widgets. Parallel code path to stream. Fails G5 and G10.
C. finalAnswer state accumulator
A new flow variable that every content-producing node appends to during execution
Previously implemented and removed. Required modifying every emitter node, duplicated content that already exists on thread.messages and in the event stream, grew state size over long sessions, needed per-node opt-out for guardrails/skills.

Option C is important to call out because three of the source docs (a2a-invoke-response-proposal.md, invoke-api-approaches.md, invoke-v2-overview.md) describe it as the winning approach. It's not — it was removed. The header comment of A2AStreamCollector.ts preserves that history.

3. What consumers see
Happy path
Agent receives "Show me my recent orders", looks up orders via a PV tool, summarises.

Request:
POST /v2/workflow-engine/wf-abc-123/invoke
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "bpc": "BPC001",
  "environment": "DEV",
  "version": "1.0",
  "interface": {
    "inputs": { "message": "Show me my recent orders" }
  },
  "options": { "sessionId": "session-001" }
}

Response:
{
  "message_id": "msg_run_1709024400_abc123",
  "role": "agent",
  "parts": [
    { "text": "Here are your recent orders:" },
    {
      "data": {
        "preText": "Looking up order...",
        "template": "<OrderTracker orderId='12345' />",
        "postText": "Order found."
      },
      "media_type": "pv"
    },
    { "text": "Let me know if you need anything else." }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "status": "COMPLETED",
    "runId": "run_1709024400_abc123",
    "sessionId": "session-001",
    "output": {
      "selectedAgentId": "wf-abc-123",
      "selectedAgentName": "Order Agent"
    }
  }
}

The client just renders parts top to bottom. Text → widget → text, in the exact order the agent produced them.

HITL interrupt
When the workflow pauses for human input (e.g. approval), V2 returns:
{
  "message_id": "msg_run_xyz",
  "role": "agent",
  "parts": [
    { "text": "Please approve this refund before I continue." }
  ],
  "metadata": {
    "status": "INTERRUPTED",
    "runId": "run_xyz",
    "sessionId": "session-001",
    "output": {
      "interrupt": {
        "checkpointId": "...",
        "nodeId": "approval-node",
        "payload": { "message": "Please approve this refund before I continue." }
      }
    }
  }
}

The consumer resumes by calling the same invokeV2 endpoint again, passing options.resume.metadata.checkpointId. The service detects the resume, replays events from the checkpoint, and returns another A2A Message (completed, interrupted again, or failed).

Error:
{
  "message_id": "msg_error_1709024400",
  "role": "agent",
  "parts": [{ "text": "Input validation failed: message: Required" }],
  "metadata": {
    "status": "FAILED",
    "errorCode": "EXECUTION_ERROR",
    "runId": "run_error_1709024400",
    "sessionId": "session-001"
  }
}
Errors always look like A2A Messages — same shape, different status.

4. How it works
4.1 The A2AMessage type
Defined in services/libs/shared/src/dtos/a2a/a2a.types.ts:

export interface A2APart {
  text?: string;
  data?: any;
  media_type?: string;    // "pv" | "a2ui" | future types
  metadata?: Record<string, any>;
}

export interface A2AMessage {
  message_id: string;
  role: 'user' | 'agent';
  parts: A2APart[];
  metadata?: Record<string, any>;
}

Three kinds of parts show up in V2 responses:

Part kind	Shape	When
Text
{ text: "..." }
Agent / LLM node produces natural language
PV widget
{ data: { preText, template, postText }, media_type: "pv" }
A Partial-View tool runs
A2UI widget
{ data: { surfaceId, rendererType, payload, ... }, media_type: "a2ui" }
An A2UI-capable tool runs

4.2 The collector (A2AStreamCollector)
Lives at services/libs/agentic-engine/src/workflow-execution/A2AStreamCollector.ts. It's a static class with one public method:
A2AStreamCollector.collect(stream$, runId, sessionId) → Promise<A2AMessage>

Internally it holds four pieces of state while the stream runs:

State	Purpose
parts: A2APart[]
The ordered output being built
textBuffer: string
In-flight text deltas between TEXT_MESSAGE_START and TEXT_MESSAGE_END
pvBuffers: Map<toolCallId, {preText, template, postText}>
In-flight PV widgets, keyed per tool call so concurrent tools don't mix
hitlInterrupt: object | null
Latest on_interrupt payload, if any

Event	Action
TEXT_MESSAGE_CONTENT
Append delta to textBuffer
TEXT_MESSAGE_END
If textBuffer non-empty, push { text: textBuffer } to parts, reset
CUSTOM / PV_PRE_RENDER
Open a new PV buffer for this toolCallId with preText = delta
CUSTOM / PV_TEMPLATE
Set template = delta on the matching PV buffer
CUSTOM / PV_POST_RENDER
Set postText, flush any pending text first, then push the PV part, then delete the buffer
CUSTOM / A2UI_MESSAGE
Parse the delta JSON, flush pending text, push an A2UI part
CUSTOM / on_interrupt
Save the interrupt payload for metadata
RUN_FINISHED
Cache event.result for metadata on completion
RUN_ERROR
Resolve immediately with an error A2A Message
Everything else
Ignored (TOOL_CALL_*, STEP_*, STATE_*, etc.)


Why text is flushed before a widget push: that's what preserves order. If the LLM says "here you go:" and then a tool fires, we need "here you go:" to land in parts before the widget, not after.

On stream complete:

Flush any leftover textBuffer.
Build metadata from RUN_FINISHED.result.output (strip the reserved messages key).
If there was an interrupt: set metadata.status = 'INTERRUPTED', put the payload under metadata.output.interrupt, push a text part with the interrupt message.
If parts is still empty (degenerate case): fall back to the last AI message from output.messages.
Resolve { message_id: 'msg_' + runId, role: 'agent', parts, metadata }.

4.3 Metadata
Top-level fields the collector always sets:

Key	Values
status
"COMPLETED" / "FAILED" / "INTERRUPTED"
errorCode
String (only on failure)
runId
run_{timestamp}_{random}
sessionId
From request or auto-generated
output
Object of non-reserved output-node keys (omitted if empty)

The only reserved key is messages (the conversation history). Everything else on the output node — selectedAgentId, selectedAgentName, user-defined keys like relatedQuestions — flows through to metadata.output.

4.4 Input validation (Start node)
The Start node (services/libs/agentic-engine/src/nodes/StartNode.ts) supports a JSON-Schema-flavored config called inputValidation:

{
  "inputValidation": {
    "properties": {
      "message":     { "type": "string", "minLength": 1 },
      "attachments": { "type": "array" },
      "count":       { "type": "number", "minimum": 1, "maximum": 100 }
    },
    "required": ["message"]
  }
}

At run start, the node builds a Zod schema from properties and runs safeParse on interface.inputs. Validation failure throws, the graph emits RUN_ERROR, and the collector surfaces a FAILED A2A Message with a human-readable issue list.

Supported types and validators:
Type	Extra validators
string
minLength, maxLength, pattern, enum
number
minimum, maximum
boolean
—
array
(items are z.any())
object
(treated as z.record(z.any()))

If inputValidation isn't configured, validation is skipped — backward compatible with existing workflows.

4.5 The V1 execution path
Happy path end-to-end, using the portal-engine service as reference (core has an identical path):

Controller (workflow-engine.controller.ts)

@Post(':id/invoke')
@Version('2')
@HttpCode(HttpStatus.OK)
async invokeV2(
  @Param('id') id: string,
  @Body() request: InvokeApiRequestV1,
): Promise<A2AMessage> {
  try {
    if (!request.options) { /* defaults */ }
    if (!request.options.sessionId) { request.options.sessionId = uuidv4(); }
    const dto = this.dtoAdapter.v1ToInternal(request);
    return await this.workflowEngine.execute(id, dto);
  } catch (error) {
    return A2AResponseTransformer.buildErrorMessage(
      error.message ?? 'An unexpected error occurred',
      `run_error_${Date.now()}`,
      request.options?.sessionId ?? 'unknown',
      'EXECUTION_ERROR',
    );
  }
}

Service (workflow-engine.service.ts)
async execute(id: string, invokeRequest: InvokeRequestDto): Promise<A2AMessage> {
  this.request.headers['RuntimeToken'] = invokeRequest.options?.runtimeToken ?? '';
  const headers = this.request.headers as Record<string, string>;

  // HITL resume path omitted for brevity
  // ...

  const { compiledGraph, processedSchema } = await this.createGraph(id, invokeRequest);
  const langfuseCallback = this.createLangfuseCallback(id, invokeRequest, ...);

  const sessionId = invokeRequest.options?.sessionId || 'default';
  const runId = `run_${Date.now()}_${Math.random().toString(36).substr(2, 9)}`;

  const adapterRequest = WorkflowExecutionHelper.buildGraphRequest(
    id, invokeRequest, interfaceInputs, headers,
    [langfuseCallback], /*...*/
    this.buildRuntimeContextForRequest(id, invokeRequest, ...),
  );
  adapterRequest.config = { ...adapterRequest.config, streamMode: 'verbose' };

  const stream$ = this.adapter.streamExecutionObservable(compiledGraph, adapterRequest);
  const tapped$ = await this.wrapV2WithSessionCapture(id, invokeRequest, sessionId, stream$);
  return A2AStreamCollector.collect(tapped$, runId, sessionId);
}

Two things to notice:

streamMode: 'verbose' is forced. minimal mode would drop PV widgets, so we override whatever the caller passed.
wrapV2WithSessionCapture taps the stream for session capture (same as streaming), then the collector subscribes to the tapped observable.

4.6 HITL resume
Same /v2/.../invoke endpoint; the caller sets options.resume.metadata.checkpointId. The service detects it, calls handleResume(id, request, headers) (shared with the stream path), unwraps the emitted { data, type } events into raw AG-UI events, and feeds them into A2AStreamCollector.collect(...). Resume responses return the same A2A shape — completed, interrupted again, or failed.

4.7 Three versions coexist
Version	Endpoint	Returns
V0 (default)
POST /workflow-engine/:id/invoke
GepReturnDto — legacy, unchanged
V1
POST /v1/workflow-engine/:id/invoke
GepReturnDto — legacy, unchanged
V2
POST /v2/workflow-engine/:id/invoke
A2AMessage — this ADR

V0/V1 stay live until we confirm no internal consumers rely on them; deprecation will be a separate ADR.

