6. What's in the canvas
These are tracked separately as UI work, but documented here so builders know where to configure V2:

Endpoints panel (frontend/src/components/canvas/panel-content/EndpointsPanelContent.tsx) — published vs development URL toggle, development token, code snippets in multiple languages, response schema + example.
Start node — builders can add typed input fields (message, attachments, or custom) with the validators listed in §4.4. inputValidation is optional.
Output node — any key a builder adds (apart from the internal messages) will show up in metadata.output of the V2 response.
Variables panel — inspect Variables / Threads / Runtime state during a run.

7. Risks and trade-offs
Risk	Why it matters	Mitigation
Invoke pays the cost of running the streaming pipeline even though it doesn't stream
Extra per-event overhead
Acceptable — dominated by LLM latency. The alternative is a second code path that will drift from stream.
A node that only updates state but doesn't emit events won't appear in parts[]
Silent content loss
Document: only streamed content reaches the response. Nodes wanting content in parts[] must emit TEXT_MESSAGE_* / CUSTOM events.
Three invoke versions now coexist
More surface to maintain
V0/V1 are frozen; deprecation tracked separately.
Legacy A2AResponseTransformer is dead code for the success path
Risk of accidental reuse
Header comment on A2AStreamCollector.ts documents the supersession. Cleanup tracked as tech debt.
AG-UI event shapes change underneath us
Breaks collector
Unit tests on the collector against representative event fixtures.
Consumers using V0/V1 assume messages is in the response
messages is reserved and excluded from metadata.output
Called out in the Endpoints panel; migration notes for V0/V1 → V2.

